aligned_segments.text: Hello, I am Lagni Patel and I recently graduated with Masters of Computer Science from North Carolina State University. Over the past few years I have worked as both data scientist and machine learning engineer and somewhere along the way I realized that what I really love is using AI for real domain specific work, solving problems that actually matter to people and not just running the models for the sake of it. As a data scientist at the NC Museum of Natural Sciences, I worked on a large project, a wildlife project called Snapshot USA, where we analyzed over 100k camera -trap images per week to estimate animal density. The data was messy, so I built a full ETL pipeline in Python to automate metadata extraction, filtering and calibration that pipeline reduced overall processing time by 65%. Once the data was clean, I trained deep learning models like InPite Torch mainly resonate for filtering classification and DPD,

prediction transformer for depth estimation. So we could calculate how far the animals are from the camera. By combining the bounding box information and learned depth maps, we help researchers move from just prediction to true population density estimation. I also built a small express .js, the portal for visualization and content -arized the whole workflow using dog codes. So anyone could use the lab to run it easily. Before that, I worked as a machine learning engineer in the mechanical and aerospace department of our university, where we studied thermal conductivity of new materials. I built end -to -end machine learning workflows in Python, applying models like linear regression, random forest and XG boost and compare all of them to predict conductivity patterns. I used Cura -based GPU acceleration to speed up the large scale regression experiments as well. Across everything that I've worked on, I've realized that machine learning only reaches its full potential when you truly understand the domain behind it. That's why I always take the time to learn whether it's how animal behavior data is collected or how material behaves under heat. I adapt quickly and I pour my heart into understanding the science or the system behind the data because that's what makes the model more meaningful. I would love to bring that same mindset to a team that's building real AI products. Thank you for listening.
